<Site title="Bio — Łukasz Żyła" current="bio">
  <section>
    <h1 class="sr-only">Bio</h1>
    <div class="prose prose--bio">
      <p>
        I am a lawyer, researcher, journalist, and open-data specialist working at
        the intersection of media, public-sector data, and artificial intelligence.
        I am co-founder of
        <a href="https://vocative.ai" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Vocative AI&nbsp;↗</a>,
        a platform that turns speech into action through intelligent voice
        automation, and of the Media 3.0 foundation, through which I have run
        open-data and media-watchdog projects since 2013.
      </p>
      <p>
        I served on two government working groups: the Working Group on Open Data at
        the Ministry of Digital Affairs and the Working Group on the Re-use of
        Public Sector Information at the Ministry of Investment and Economic
        Development. I have delivered training programs for organizations including
        Gazeta Wyborcza, Polska Press, and the Information Society Development
        Foundation (Fundacja Rozwoju Społeczeństwa Informacyjnego). In 2018, I
        trained the open-data coordinators of all Polish ministries and central
        government institutions, and through a Facebook-funded digital-skills
        initiative my fellow trainers and I helped educate more than 11,000
        participants.
      </p>
      <p>
        I collaborated with Gazeta Wyborcza as a journalist (2012–2014) and served
        as Editor-in-Chief of regional media in Silesia (Wydawnictwo Nowiny,
        2009–2012). Over the years I have designed and co-developed roughly seventy
        web applications for processing and analyzing public-sector data. These
        include civic-tech tools such as
        <a href="https://ktorzadzi.pl" target="_blank" rel="noopener">KtoRządzi.pl&nbsp;↗</a>,
        which maps the connections between political power and business by combining
        official public registers, and a data tool built within Google's Digital
        News Initiative. I also organize HackHeroes, a nationwide educational
        hackathon.
      </p>
      <p>
        Alongside my legal and journalistic work, I am a sound and audiovisual
        artist performing under the alias <em>złe oko</em> (“evil eye”), working
        with generative systems, real-time neural audio synthesis, and
        experimental sound. I have created and curated art events, including the
        Insomnia Art Festival and immersive concert projects.
      </p>
      <p>
        My interest in public affairs and the humanities began early. In July 2001,
        on the strength of a literary piece on addiction, I was selected as a member
        of the Children and Youth Parliament (Sejm Dzieci i Młodzieży), a mandate
        issued by the Chancellery of the Sejm. Having taken my seat after “a few”
        glasses of good wine, I was quite possibly the youngest inebriated member of
        parliament in the Sejm's history. Around the same time I attended the Flying
        University of “Znak”, following lectures by Ryszard Kapuściński, Norman
        Davies, Adam Zagajewski, and others.
      </p>
      <p>
        I hold a law degree from the European University of Law and Administration
        (EWSPA), affiliated with the Polish Academy of Sciences, and completed
        postgraduate studies in Machine Learning and Data Science at the University
        of Economics in Katowice. I also studied Political Science at the
        Jagiellonian University and Philosophy, Sociology, and Spanish at the
        University of Silesia.
      </p>
      <p>
        I am the author of the book <em>Data Journalism and Data Storytelling</em>
        (Dziennikarstwo danych i data storytelling), published by Helion, and
        co-author of a University of Wrocław monograph on open data and data
        storytelling. I have taught in the Social Informatics program at AGH
        University of Krakow (2022–2024), running classes on designing and managing
        applications and social startups.
      </p>
      <p>
        Together with the Media 3.0/SAP team, I won third place in the first Polish
        Government Open Data Hackathon and later mentored its next edition. In 2012,
        I translated Alejandro Jodorowsky's <em>Psychomagic</em> (Psychomagia) from
        Spanish into Polish. I work in Polish and English, and translate from
        Spanish and Japanese.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>
</Site>
